===Etymology 1===
{{IPAfont|⟨to<sub>2</sub>ki<sub>1</sub>⟩}} → *{{IPAfont|/təkʲi/}} → {{IPAfont|/toki/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}, from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*təki}}. First attested in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712 {{CE}}.<ref name="KDJC">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten Concise}}</ref>

There are various theories regarding the ultimate derivation.
* Possibly a fusion of {{prefix|ja|常|tr1=toko|pos1=[[prefix]] for “[[always]], [[unchanging]]”|い|tr2=i|pos2=Old Japanese nominal particle}}.
: However, the sense of “unchanging” does not fit well with the sense of “the passing of time”.  Separately, the phonetics of {{cog-lite|ojp|-}} {{IPAfont|⟨ki<sub>1</sub>⟩}} → {{IPAfont|/kʲi/}} appear to [[contraindicate]] a fusion of {{IPAfont|/ko/}} + {{IPAfont|/i/}}, which resulted in {{IPAfont|⟨ki<sub>2</sub>⟩}} → {{IPAfont|/kʷi/}} as seen at {{m|ja|木}}.
* Possibly derived from or otherwise related to {{m|ja|疾し||tr=toshi|sharp; happening quickly}}, cognate with {{m|ja|研ぐ||tr=togu|to sharpen}}.
: However, the historical spelling of ''toshi'' was ''to<sub>1</sub>(si)'', as in {{lang|ojp|那杼佐祁流'''斗'''米}} (''nado<sub>1</sub> sake<sub>1</sub>ru '''to<sub>1</sub>''' me<sub>2</sub>'', "why do you have knife cutting eyes").<ref name="JDB">{{R:JDB|page=493}}</ref>
* Possibly related to {{m|ja|年||tr=toshi|year}}.

